{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"PASS 1 review (T3 Integration feasibility — git CLI plumbing). Recording findings + affirmations.\n\nAFFIRMATIONS (T3 criteria satisfied):\n- Integration achievable as described: the plan integrates the git CLI via standard plumbing (`git fetch origin`, `rev-parse`-style ref resolution, `read-tree`, `checkout-index`) — all real, extant git subcommands. `git fetch origin` and `rev-parse` are already used in this codebase (src/rebar/_engine_support/reads.py, src/rebar/signing.py:309, src/rebar/llm/workflow/snapshot.py:84), so those are MATCH/already-used integrations.\n- Auth/HTTPS precondition stated: AC \"Private-repo fetch failures surface a descriptive, actionable credential error\" names the auth precondition for `git fetch origin`.\n- Portability preconditions stated: \"pure-Python tar-free extraction, gettempdir/mkdtemp, flock+mkdir fallback, POSIX\"; the EFS/NFS flock caveat is tracked on alto-fruit-punch.\n- Spike machinery present: the plan notes a spike already corrected the janitor primitive (dropped PID lease for kernel guarantees), showing capability gaps get routed to a spike.\n\nFINDINGS:\n\n- [ ] Ground the \"faithful (NOT lossy `git archive`) materialization via `read-tree` + `checkout-index`\" claim against the specific content gaps it must close, or route the faithfulness comparison to a spike before committing. [criteria: T3] [location: plan \"What\" — \"Materialization is faithful (read-tree + checkout-index, NOT lossy git archive)\"]\n  Evidence: The existing snapshot path (src/rebar/llm/workflow/snapshot.py) is the `git archive` implementation the plan replaces; its docstring (lines 23-27) documents PRECISELY what `git archive` drops: `.gitattributes export-ignore` paths, submodule contents (stops at the gitlink), and Git-LFS files (pointer text, not smudged content). The plan asserts the new `read-tree`+`checkout-index` primitive is \"faithful\" but does not name WHICH of those gaps it closes, nor verify `checkout-index` doesn't share them — `checkout-index` populates from the index and likewise does NOT recurse into submodule gitlinks, and whether it smudges LFS / applies export-ignore depends on the index population and configured filters. This is the load-bearing, asserted-but-unverified capability the whole \"faithful\" success criterion rests on (T3: asserted-but-unverified external capability = MAJOR). suggested_fix: empty (the correct faithfulness target — track export-ignore? submodules? LFS smudge? — is a design call I can't confidently fix from the plan text; either enumerate the gap closed and cite the git plumbing that closes it, or add a spike that diffs `git archive`-tree vs `read-tree`+`checkout-index`-tree on a repo exercising submodules/LFS/export-ignore).\n\n- [ ] State the `read-tree` + `checkout-index` invocation's index/work-tree precondition that makes it \"lock-free\" and \"without git-lock contention,\" since these plumbing commands normally operate on an index file (.git/index) that concurrent ops would contend on. [criteria: T3] [location: plan AC \"Concurrent gates ... run without git-lock contention\"; \"What\" — \"lock-free materialization\"]\n  Evidence: AC-4 requires \"no worktrees; atomic population\" and the success criteria say \"lock-free.\" `git read-tree`/`checkout-index` default to the repo's single .git/index, which IS a lock point (index.lock) — the lock-free property depends on a stated mechanism (e.g., a per-op GIT_INDEX_FILE in a tempdir, or `--prefix` checkout against an ephemeral index). The plan asserts lock-free materialization but does not name the index-isolation mechanism that delivers it; this is the integration detail that determines whether the concurrency AC is technically feasible as described. suggested_fix: empty."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782519605716184001,"uuid":"3525f707-27a9-40b9-821f-64b7f6eeefe1"}